{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537100"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:13:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:13:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15903"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15903"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.04,0.78,0.02,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8594"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103372"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8594","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8594"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15903"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85793"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"619"},{"type":"tags","id":"1201"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4656"},{"type":"tags","id":"4748"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"6442"},{"type":"tags","id":"9663"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20597"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35499"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35500"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103372"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a five-day history of pain in his lower abdomen and perineum. He reports having a three-week history of dysuria, urinary frequency, and purulent urethral discharge but did not seek medical attention as he was travelling through South-East Asia for the past two months. He reports having unprotected sexual intercourse with multiple people whilst travelling. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.  He is flying to New Zealand tomorrow and is not keen to take any regular medication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His has mild suprapubic discomfort on deep palpation. There is thick yellow-green discharge at the urethral meatus, though the genitals otherwise appear normal. Digital rectal examination reveals a tender, boggy prostate. Gram stain of the urethral discharge shows intracellular gram-negative diplococci.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate antibiotic treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Doxycycline 100 mg orally twice daily for 14 days","Ciprofloxacin 500 mg orally twice daily for 14 days","Ceftriaxone 500 mg intramuscularly as a single dose plus azithromycin 1 g orally as a single dose","Amoxicillin-clavulanate 875/125 mg orally twice daily for 14 days","Trimethoprim 300 mg orally once daily for 14 days"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and signs consistent with acute prostatitis, with Gram stain confirming \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E as the causative organism. The presentation is typical, with dysuria, frequency, suprapubic and perineal pain, and a tender prostate on examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECeftriaxone plus azithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate treatment for gonococcal prostatitis. A single dose of intramuscular ceftriaxone plus oral azithromycin is recommended. The addition of azithromycin is important as co-infection with \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E is common, occurring in up to 50% of cases. Additionally, the use of azithromycin alongside ceftriaxone helps prevent the development of resistant gonococci, and is appropriate for patients who are unlikely to be compliant with two weeks of treatment with doxycycline after the intramuscular ceftriaxone injection as well.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDoxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be appropriate for chlamydial infection but is not adequate for treating gonorrhoea due to widespread resistance.  If the patient was compliant with ongoing treatment, an alternate treatment would be ceftriaxone intramuscular single dose injection and two weeks of doxycycline orally depending on local resistance patterns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECiprofloxacin\u003C/strong\u003E was previously used for gonorrhoea but is no longer recommended due to high rates of resistance, particularly in South-East Asia where resistance rates exceed 90% in some regions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin-clavulanate\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as resistance is common and it does not achieve adequate prostatic tissue levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrimethoprim\u003C/strong\u003E is typically the first-line empiric treatment for bacterial prostatitis. However, it has no role in the treatment of gonococcal infection, which is confirmed in this case by the Gram stain findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to consider the potential of a sexually-transmitted infection causing prostatitis in patients under 35 years of age, or older patients who engage in high-risk sexual behaviours. Whilst it is an uncommon complication, both \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis \u003C/em\u003Eand \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E have the potential to cause prostatitis and there have been case reports of mycoplasma-associated prostatitis. Contact tracing may be difficult due to the patient\u0027s recent travel history, however every attempt should be made to contact every sexual partner in the previous two months. Following treatment, the patient should abstain from sexually activity for seven days, and should return for a test-of-cure in two weeks to ensure the infection has resolved.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Neisseria gonorrhoeae is a potential cause of acute prostatitis in sexually active men.","Symptoms of acute prostatitis include dysuria, urinary frequency, suprapubic and perineal pain, and tender prostate on examination.","Ceftriaxone plus azithromycin is the recommended treatment for gonococcal prostatitis due to high resistance rates to other antibiotics."],"references":["Brede CM, Shoskes DA. The etiology and management of acute prostatitis. Nature Reviews Urology. 2011 Mar 15;8(4):207\u201312. Available at: https://www.nature.com/articles/nrurol.2011.22","Dickson G. Prostatitis: diagnosis and treatment. Aust Fam Physician. 2013 Apr;42(4):220\u20134. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2013/april/prostatitis","Australian STI Management Guidelines: http://www.sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/gonorrhoea"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85793"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15903"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85793","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85793"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-21T20:10:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-21T20:13:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8594"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103372"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ud